{{unreferenced|date=March 2007}}
The '''Action at Kalmas''' was a battle between the [[British Army]] and a group of [[guerrilla]] fighters in [[Afghanistan]] in 1916.

On 26 September 1916 an action took place at [[Kalmas]], thirty miles north of [[Nasratabad Sipi]], between a small British detachment and some gun-runners moving a convoy of arms towards [[Afghanistan]]. 2nd-Lt [[B. W. Wahl]], with 23 [[sowar]]s of the [[23rd Light Cavalry]] and 36 levies, surprised and attacked the gun-runners. The whole convoy was captured, four of its escort being killed and one taken prisoner. However, Lt Wahl and one sowar of the 23rd Light Cavalry were killed in the cavalry charge which opened the action.

