{{Infobox company | name = A.L. Galliano Bankers | logo = | caption = Early photo of Galliano's Bank in [[Main Street, Gibraltar]] | type = | genre = | fate = Acquired | predecessor = | successor = [[Jyske Bank]] | foundation = [[Gibraltar]] ({{Start date|1855}}) | founder = [[Antonio Luis Galliano]] | defunct = {{End date|1997}} | location_city = | location_country = | location = [[Main Street, Gibraltar]] | locations = | area_served = Gibraltar | key_people = [[Francis Galliano]] | industry = [[Banking]] | products = | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | aum = | assets = | equity = | owner = | num_employees = | parent = | subsid = | homepage = | footnotes = | intl = }} '''Banco Galliano''' was the oldest [[bank]] in the [[British overseas territories|British overseas territory]] of [[Gibraltar]].
==History== In 1855 [[Antonio Luis Galliano]] (1803–1866) and his family, immigrants from [[Genoa]] via [[Cádiz]], established '''A.L. Galliano Bankers''' in Gibraltar, better known as ''Banco Galliano'' in [[Spanish language|Spanish]], or ''Galliano's Bank'' in [[English language|English]]. This family-owned bank was Gibraltar’s oldest bank, though it did not [[incorporation (business)|incorporate]] until August 1978. (Before that it was a partnership.) In 1987 [[Jyske Bank]] acquired Banco Galliano renaming it '''Jyske Bank (Gibraltar) Limited'''.<ref>[http://www.ecbs.org/banks/gibraltar/jyske-bank-gibraltar-ltd./view-details.html Jyske Bank (Gibraltar) Limited - History]</ref>
From the latter half of the 19th century, Galliano's bank started to face competition. The [[Anglo-Egyptian Bank]] (later [[Barclays]]) opened a branch in 1888, and [[Crédit Foncier de France|Credit Foncier]] (later [[Crédit Agricole]]) entered in 1920. There were also, by the start of the 20th century, four other small, family-owned banks - [[Cuby Brothers]], [[Benzecry]] (''El Banquerito''), [[Rugeroni Brothers]], and [[Marrache and Sons]] - but by 1940 these had ceased operating.
A.L. Galliano Bankers survived the [[Great Depression]], the [[Spanish Civil War]], and both [[world war]]s, albeit with difficulty. [[Gibraltarian people|Gibraltarian]] [[Francis Galliano|Francis (Paco) Galliano]] [[OBE]], the last Galliano to own and run the bank, entered the bank in 1944 at the age of 17. He became a [[partner (business rank)|partner]] in 1953 and the senior partner in 1964. His son, [[Frank Galliano]] was General Manager until the takeover.
==Trivia== [[File:Andrew Galliano playing guitar (1913).jpg|thumb|[[Andrew Galliano]], ex Senior Partner, playing a [[Classical guitar|Spanish guitar]] by [[Joséf Pagés]].]] In 1822, [[Spanish people|Spanish]] the [[luthier|guitar-maker]] [[Joséf Pagés]] made a [[Classical guitar|Spanish guitar]] that came to belong to members of the Galliano family. Paco Galliano sold it in 2008 for [[Pound sterling|£]]6,600.<ref>[http://www.bonhams.com/cgi-bin/public.sh/pubweb/publicSite.r?sContinent=EUR&screen=lotdetailsNoFlash&iSaleItemNo=3834985&iSaleNo=16003&iSaleSectionNo=1 Bonhams - A Spanish Six-course Guitar by Josef Pages, Cadiz 1822]</ref>
