[[Image:Dab-Chrobry-2007.jpg|300px|thumb|Chrobry Oak]]
The '''Chrobry Oak''' is an [[English oak|oak]] tree, the largest oak in [[Poland]] and one of the biggest in [[Europe]].

It is monumental oak with single-stemmed, hollow [[Trunk (botany)|trunk]], its girth was 1004&nbsp;cm, height – 26&nbsp;m and volume – 90&nbsp;m³ (in 2014). Moreover, it is the oldest oak tree in Poland. Age of the ''Chrobry'' is about 760 years, according to [[dendrochronology|dendrochronological research]].<ref name=drzewapolski>Krzysztof Borkowski, Robert Tomusiak, Paweł Zarzyński. ''Drzewa Polski''. 2016. p.154–157</ref>

Oak was officially preserved (as a natural monument) since 1966{{R|drzewapolski}}.

''Chrobry'' was measured in 1908 at the earliest, by Theodor Schube (German botanist), girth of the tree was 861&nbsp;cm{{R|drzewapolski}}.

Tree was set on fire by vandals on November 2014. ''Chrobry'' remained in fatal condition, but in 2015 part of the crown was still alive{{R|drzewapolski}}.

